---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="shuttle rollback"
  description="Roll back to the previous deployment or a specific image tag, with health checks and proxy switching."
  section="commands"
>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle rollback</code> reverts your app to a previous deployment. It starts containers
    from an already-present image (no build step), runs health checks, atomically switches the
    proxy, drains the current containers, and updates the deployment state. The operation fires
    webhook notifications on completion.
  </p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle rollback                    # roll back to previous_tag from state.json
shuttle rollback --to &lt;tag&gt;        # roll back to a specific image tag
</code></pre>

  <h2>Flags</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Flag</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>--to &lt;tag&gt;</code></td>
        <td>Target image tag to roll back to (e.g., <code>shuttle/my-app:deploy-20260326-abc1234</code>). Defaults to <code>previous_tag</code> from <code>state.json</code>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>--config &lt;path&gt;</code></td>
        <td>Explicit path to <code>shuttle.yml</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>--env &lt;name&gt;</code></td>
        <td>Load <code>shuttle.&lt;name&gt;.yml</code> overlay</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>6-step rollback process</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Resolve target tag</strong> — reads <code>state.json</code> from
      <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/</code> on the server. Uses <code>--to</code> if provided,
      otherwise falls back to <code>previous_tag</code>. Throws if no previous tag exists.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Start rollback containers</strong> — for each service, stops any stale container
      on the inactive slot and starts a new container from the rollback image. No image build
      or transfer occurs — the image must already be present on the server.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Health check</strong> — runs the health check for the first service (if configured)
      against the new containers. Uses the same retry and timeout settings as a normal deploy.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Switch proxy upstream</strong> — Caddy is updated to point to the rollback
      containers. No connections are dropped.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Drain old containers</strong> — stops the currently active containers after the
      proxy has switched. Respects <code>deploy.blue_green.drain_timeout</code> (default: 30s).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Update deployment state</strong> — writes updated <code>state.json</code> with the
      rollback tag as <code>active_tag</code> and the previous active tag as <code>previous_tag</code>.
      The version counter increments — rollbacks are tracked as deployments.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Listing available versions</h2>
  <p>
    Available rollback targets are Docker images with the <code>shuttle/&lt;app&gt;:deploy-</code>
    prefix currently present on the server. You can list them directly:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">ssh deploy@your-server "docker images 'shuttle/my-app:deploy-*' --format '&#123;&#123;.Tag&#125;&#125;'"
# deploy-20260326-abc1234
# deploy-20260325-def5678
# deploy-20260324-ghi9012
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Shuttle retains the last <code>deploy.retain</code> images (default: 3) on the server, so you
    can roll back up to 3 releases by default.
  </p>

  <h2>Rolling back to a specific version</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle rollback --to shuttle/my-app:deploy-20260325-def5678
</code></pre>

  <h2>Webhook notifications</h2>
  <p>
    Rollback fires <code>rollback_succeeded</code> or <code>rollback_failed</code> webhook events
    to all URLs configured under <code>notifications.webhooks</code>. This is the same
    notification system as deploy events.
  </p>

  <h2>Multi-server rollback</h2>
  <p>
    Rollback runs sequentially across hosts (not in parallel). Each host acquires its deploy lock
    before starting and releases it after completion, preventing concurrent rollbacks on the same
    host.
  </p>

  <h2>No previous version available</h2>
  <p>
    If this is the first deploy or the state file has no <code>previous_tag</code> entry,
    <code>shuttle rollback</code> without <code>--to</code> will fail with:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">DeployError: No previous version available to roll back to for "my-app" on 203.0.113.10
</code></pre>
  <p>
    In this case, use <code>--to</code> with an explicit image tag that is present on the server.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
